1. [CRITICAL] Web3 Identity Spoofing (Naive
Authentication)
Location: AuthContext.jsx (Lines 48–50) and api.js (Line 72)
The Vulnerability
The current implementation uses "Naive Auth.
" The frontend simply connects to Phantom,
retrieves a public key string, and sends that string to the backend to "link" the wallet.
●
The Exploit: A malicious actor can bypass the UI entirely. By calling the
/api/users/wallet/ endpoint via the browser console or Postman with a stolen
public key string, they can claim ownership of any high-reputation wallet (e.g., a Verifier’s
wallet) without actually owning the private keys.
Required Fix: Challenge-Response Nonce Flow
We must shift from "Tell the backend my address" to "Prove I own this address.
"
Step A: Backend (Django)
1. Create a /api/users/nonce/ endpoint.
2. When called, generate a random, time-sensitive string (Nonce) and store it in the user's
profile or cache.
3. 4. Update the linkWallet view to require two fields: wallet_address and signature.
Use pynacl or solders to cryptographically verify that the signature was created by
that wallet_address signing the nonce.
Step B: Frontend (React)
1. 2. Request: Call /api/users/nonce/ to get the challenge string.
Sign: Use window.solana.signMessage() to have the user sign the nonce in their
wallet.
3. Submit: Send the resulting signature and the public key to the backend.
